Two
 hours after threats were sent to officials and the Harvard Crimson 
newspaper, authorities had already decided they were likely a hoax.

Investigators from several agencies 
searched the buildings for hours before determining there were no 
explosives. One of the buildings was a freshman dormitory; classes are 
held in the other three.

In a statement to the Harvard community, Harvard Executive
Vice President Katie Lapp said that the buildings were evacuated ‘out of an
abundance of caution’ and that activities at the Ivy League school in Cambridge
were returning to normal.

‘I am relieved to report that no suspicious devices were
found,’ Lapp said in her statement.

